Here are both approaches using Shell navigation and `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Navigate with a string ID:**

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
```

**2. Navigate with a full object:**

```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
```

**Receiving both in the ViewModel via `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter (arrives as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from a service, etc.
            LoadProduct(productId);
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (arrives as the original type)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }

    private async void LoadProduct(string id)
    {
        Product p = await _productService.GetByIdAsync(id);
        Name = p.Name;
        Price = p.Price;
    }
}
```

**Route registration (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`):**

```csharp
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `?key=value` in URI | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Type in `ApplyQueryAttributes`** | `string` | Original CLR type |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, deep links | Complex objects already in memory |

String params survive deep links/URLs; object params don't. Use string IDs for bookmarkable routes and objects for in-app navigation with data you already have.
